What I Did


I first forked the original repository to my GitHub account, and then added my JSON file to the contributors section by creating a pull request.

All dependencies were installed using `npm install`, after which the project was built with `npm run build`. Finally, I executed the client tests using `npm run test-client`, and all tests passed successfully.

I installed Ollama and initially tried running Llama 3, but it failed due to insufficient memory on my system. I then switched to TinyLlama, which ran successfully, and verified it by running a prompt test that produced the expected output.


What I Learned


This exercise has allowed me to get an insight into how the whole project setup process looks like, including installation of dependencies and other tests.

I had my first hands-on experience with a locally installed LLM, during which I found out that the size of a model is one of the factors that determines its capability to run, while the small models have their own value and should be taken seriously.

Finally, I also had a chance to explore the SMILE approach, which focuses more on understanding why something has been done, as compared to just doing that thing.
